		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Zombies: how do they work?
				</h2>
				

						
							
							
							
						
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1785487">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Linked to the World War Z thread, but in general a question that has arisen from every single zombie story I have ever read - how do they work?<br />
<br />
Specifically, how do you end up with giant hordes of zombies?<br />
<br />
Zombies attack the living. You see them tear apart and devour anyone they can get their hands on. So where do the new zombies come from? Yes some people will get bitten and then escape to become infected, but the vast majority of people who get bitten don't escape but get ripped to shreds and slaughtered by the zombies which prevents them becoming a zombie or spreading it. <br />
<br />
It seems as though zombies run around, biting people once and then leaving them alone to turn. That would make more sense but is absolutely not the image we see in film / games at all. People talk about the exponential factor but the reality is most zombie victims just end up dead and in someone's stomach - only a few will escape to turn and start the cycle again. <br />
<br />
I just don't see how you end up with the 'end of the world' scenarios given how zombies behave. They aren't the Borg and forcibly converting people isn't their goal - they want to kill, rip apart and devour their victims. That doesn't leave many people to carry on zombification...
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
