				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Zombies: how do they work?
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1785522">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							In the followup to world war z, the zombie survival guide, the outbreak is always due to a virus called (iirc) Selenium. Because the original world war z/zsg zombies are slow moving, a bite might be a victims first warning. They were unaware of the zombie threat and then flee.<br />
<br />
To which they are treated, and in recuperation/ambulance die and infect others, etc etc.<br />
<br />
The majority of those who fal victim are unaware of zombie movie protocol, and the zombies just look like live, sick or disillusioned individuals, and fall victim to their own compassion with humnanity; even a crack head attacking them is likely just going for their wallet, so a bite seems very superficial in the big scheme of things. But once they are bit, they run and infect others, and the original zombie is still there.<br />
<br />
The majority of horror, including, but not limited to werewolves, vampires and zombies are based on the rabies virus, especially vampires. Once someone is infected with rabies they &quot;turn&quot; and develop aversions to light, are incurable (if not immediately treated), and are essentially the walking dead. Those infected by rabies are not invisible in a mirror, but cease to recognize their own reflection as themselves.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
