				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Zombies: how do they work?
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1785525">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Wool</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1785524#post1785524" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">I think they just don't finish what they eat. It isn't unusual to see zombies with their guts spilling out for no reason. Maybe once the flesh goes cold zombies are no longer interested in it. Without warm gushing blood it just isn't as tasty! I've never seen a zombie eating another zombie afterall.<br />
<br />
The thing I don't get about zombies is how in apocalypse films they constantly manage to topple civilization. Initial confusion and the insidious nature of the &quot;disease&quot; would cause damage at first, but modern weapons are incredibly efficient and ending human lives. It seems like it would be incredibly trivial to just mow them down by the thousands.<br />
<br />
You always seem to see abandoned tanks and IFVs next to all the abandoned cars, but why? A zombie isn't getting in there, and it doesn't even have to waste ammo, just run over them. It's supposed to make us think that even the military couldn't stand up to the terrible zombie hordes, but I don't buy it and have never bought it. Zombies are fodder for inexperienced newbs who need something more dangerous than giant rats to fight.<br />
<br />
<img src="images/smilies/monkeydance.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Dance Like a Monkey!" class="inlineimg" /></div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>They never do quite explain how zombies defeat a tank.  Even if the threat is airborne viral in the &quot;red zone&quot; a tank when closed up has full NBC protection as far as I know.(That is Nuclear Biological Chemical,  Not protection from bad reality shows on the NBC television network.)
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
